It seems you have also switched to using `min_similarity` instead of `average_similarity` in benchmark. I strongly believe this will encourage one person submitting a bunch of identical solutions and hoping for luck.

There is a high probability that one of the 20 outputs will have very low similarity (<0.4) when you try to optimize the model to run significantly faster than the baseline.
As the baseline runs 20 inference steps instead of 50, reducing generation_time becomes extremely important. Making the model run significantly faster than baseline is a must to be competitive. A submission then only has a chance of winning if it is lucky enough to not have any outputs with low similarity.
for now subnet isnt working at all.

By the way, current resnet embedding calculation also introduces another large source of randomness. Adding `torch.manual_seed(0)` to `compare_outputs` can ensure the resnet embedding computation is deterministic among submissions.

With these arguments, I firmly believe that the current reward mechanism includes too much uncertainty. Luck helps a submission win, not the goodness of its optimization. Here are some approaches that I think can reduce randomness a lot:

- Use `average_similarity` instead of `min_similarity` or a weighted average like `0.8 * average_similarity + 0.2 * min_similarity`.
- Add `torch.manual_seed(seed)` to `compare_outputs`, with `seed` needs to be hard-coded.
- Run 50 steps with the baseline if you want to emphasize the importance of `min_similarity`.
